{"title_page": "The Lady's and Gentleman's Diary", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''The Lady's and Gentleman's Diary''''' was a [[recreational mathematics]] magazine formed as a successor of ''[[The Ladies' Diary]]'' and ''[[Gentleman's Diary]]'' in 1841. It was published annually between 1841 and 1871<ref name=iona/> by the Company of Stationers; its editor from 1844 to 1865 was [[Wesley S. B. Woolhouse]]. It consisted mostly of problems posed by its readers, with their solutions given in later volumes, though it also contained word puzzles and poetry. The magazine was based in [[London]]. It ceased publication in 1871.<ref name=\"iona\">{{cite book|author=Iona Italia|title=The Rise of Literary Journalism in the Eighteenth Century: Anxious Employment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DxKtVeAoVSUC&pg=PA5|accessdate=22 October 2016|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-34392-3|page=5}}</ref> This should not be confused with ''Ladies and Gentlemens Diary, or Royal Almanack'' (1775 to 1786) which was printed by Thomas Carnan and edited by [[Reuben Burrow]] and was a short lived competitor to ''The Ladies' Diary''.\n\n[[Kirkman's schoolgirl problem]] originated in a question in the magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000071981 ''Lady's and Gentleman's Diary''] at the HathiTrust digital library.\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/title/ladys-and-gentlemans-diary/oclc/5536712 WorldCat record]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lady's and Gentleman's Diary}}\n[[Category:British annual magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:London magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1841]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1871]]\n[[Category:Mathematics magazines]]\n[[Category:Recreational mathematics]]\n\n\n{{UK-mag-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Italic title}}\n'''''The Lady's and Gentleman's Diary''''' was a [[recreational mathematics]] magazine formed as a successor of ''[[The Ladies' Diary]]'' and ''[[Gentleman's Diary]]'' in 1841. It was published annually between 1841 and 1871<ref name=iona/> by the Company of Stationers; its editor from 1844 to 1865 was [[Wesley S. B. Woolhouse]]. It consisted mostly of problems posed by its readers, with their solutions given in later volumes, though it also contained word puzzles and poetry. The magazine was based in [[London]]. It ceased publication in 1871.<ref name=\"iona\">{{cite book|author=Iona Italia|title=The Rise of Literary Journalism in the Eighteenth Century: Anxious Employment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DxKtVeAoVSUC&pg=PA5|accessdate=22 October 2016|year=2005|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-34392-3|page=5}}</ref> This should not be confused with ''Ladies and Gentlemens Diary, or Royal Almanack'' (1775 to 1786) which was printed by Thomas Carnan and edited by [[Reuben Burrow]] and was a short lived competitor to ''The Ladies' Diary''.\n\n[[Kirkman's schoolgirl problem]] originated in a question in the magazine.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/000071981 ''Lady's and Gentleman's Diary''] at the HathiTrust digital library.\n*[http://www.worldcat.org/title/ladys-and-gentlemans-diary/oclc/5536712 WorldCat record]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lady's and Gentleman's Diary}}\n[[Category:Annual magazines]]\n[[Category:British magazines]]\n[[Category:Defunct magazines of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:London magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1841]]\n[[Category:Magazines disestablished in 1871]]\n[[Category:Mathematics magazines]]\n[[Category:Recreational mathematics]]\n\n\n{{UK-mag-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Lady%27s_and_Gentleman%27s_Diary"}
{"title_page": "Combs Reservoir", "text_new": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Combs Reservoir\n| image = Combs Reservoir from Castle Naze.jpg\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|18|43|N|1|57|11|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|name=Combs Reservoir}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = Meverill Brook and Pyegreave Brook\n| outflow = [[Randall Carr]] Brook\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = {{Convert|1|km|1}}\n| width = {{Convert|0.5|km|1}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Combs Reservoir from Whitehills by Dave Dunford.jpg|thumb|265x265px|Combs Reservoir from Whitehills]]\n'''Combs Reservoir''' is a canal-feeder reservoir in the [[Peak District National Park]], close to [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] village in [[Derbyshire]]. The town of [[Whaley Bridge|Chapel-en-le-Frith]] lies about 1km to the east of the reservoir.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1000334.pdf|title=COMBS RESERVOIR SSSI|last=|first=|date=20 October 1986|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs was built in 1797 as the first reservoir to feed the [[Peak Forest Canal]] (which opened in 1800) at [[Whaley Bridge]]. The canal was critical for transporting goods to and from the corn mills, cotton factories, collieries and other local industry, as well as connecting to the [[Ashton Canal]] for the nearby limestone quarries. In 1831 the [[Macclesfield Canal]] was completed, which was connected to the Peak Forest Canal at [[Marple, Greater Manchester|Marple]]. The [[Toddbrook Reservoir]] at Whaley Bridge was built as an additional feeder reservoir and the dam at Combs Reservoir was raised between 1834 and 1840, in order to meet the demand for a greater water supply to the extended canal system. By the 1940s use of these canals for transporting industrial goods had ended. The reservoir is now owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/history/CombsHistory.pdf|title=The History of Combs Sailing Club|last=Broadbent|first=Sandy|date=2000|website=Combs Sailing Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buxton]] to [[Manchester]] railway line runs between Combs Reservoir and Combs village to the south and alongside the western shore.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe reservoir is overlooked by [[Eccles Pike]] hill from the north and from the south by the [[Iron Age]] promontory hillfort Castle Naze, at the northern end of [[Combs Moss]]. Castle Naze is a protected [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1009294|desc=Promontory fort on Combs Edge, Chapel-en-le-Frith|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Reservoir is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). It is particularly important for its 'ephemeral [[bryophyte]]' mosses (such as the rare ''physcomitrium sphaericum'') and [[Marchantiophyta|liverworts]] (''ricca glauca'' and ''fossombronia wondraczekii''). The area is a rich habitat for birdlife including the [[great crested grebe]], [[little ringed plover]], [[snipe]] and [[lapwing]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCombs Sailing Club has used the reservoir for sailing training and racing since 1950.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/index.php|title=Combs Sailing Club Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.combssailingclub.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English reservoir}}\n{{Infobox body of water\n| name = Combs Reservoir\n| image = Combs Reservoir from Castle Naze.jpg\n| caption = \n| image_bathymetry = \n| caption_bathymetry = \n| location = [[Derbyshire]]\n| coords = {{coord|53|18|43|N|1|57|11|W|type:waterbody_region:GB|name=Combs Reservoir}}\n| type = [[reservoir]]\n| inflow = Meverill Brook and Pyegreave Brook\n| outflow = [[Randall Carr]] Brook\n| catchment = \n| basin_countries = United Kingdom\n| length = {{Convert|1|km|1}}\n| width = {{Convert|0.5|km|1}}\n| area = \n| depth = \n| max-depth = \n| volume = \n| residence_time = \n| shore = \n| elevation = \n| islands = \n| cities = \n}}{{Use dmy dates|date = March 2020}}\n\n{{Use British English|date=March 2020}}\n[[File:Combs Reservoir from Whitehills by Dave Dunford.jpg|thumb|265x265px|Combs Reservoir from Whitehills]]\n'''Combs Reservoir''' is a canal-feeder reservoir in the [[Peak District National Park]], nearby [[Combs, Derbyshire|Combs]] village in [[Derbyshire]]. The town of [[Whaley Bridge|Chapel-en-le-Frith]] lies about 1km to the east of the reservoir.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/PDFsForWeb/Citation/1000334.pdf|title=COMBS RESERVOIR SSSI|last=|first=|date=20 October 1986|website=Natural England|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs was built in 1797 as the first reservoir to feed the [[Peak Forest Canal]] (which opened in 1800) at [[Whaley Bridge]]. The canal was critical for transporting goods to and from the corn mills, cotton factories, collieries and other local industry, as well as connecting to the [[Ashton Canal]] for the nearby limestone quarries. In 1831 the [[Macclesfield Canal]] was completed, which was connected to the Peak Forest Canal at [[Marple, Greater Manchester|Marple]]. The [[Toddbrook Reservoir]] at Whaley Bridge was built as an additional feeder reservoir and the dam at Combs Reservoir was raised between 1834 and 1840 to meet the demand for a greater water supply to the extended canal system. By the 1940s use of these canals for transporting industrial goods had ended. The reservoir is now owned by the [[Canal & River Trust]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/history/CombsHistory.pdf|title=The History of Combs Sailing Club|last=Broadbent|first=Sandy|date=2000|website=Combs Sailing Club|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Buxton]] to [[Manchester]] railway line runs between Combs Reservoir and Combs village to the south and alongside the western shore.<ref name=\"OS\">[[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' map OL24W, 1:25,000 series.</ref>\n\nThe reservoir is overlooked by [[Eccles Pike]] hill from the north and from the south by the [[Iron Age]] promontory hillfort Castle Naze at the northern end of [[Combs Moss]]. Castle Naze is a protected [[Scheduled monument|Scheduled Monument]].<ref>{{NHLE|num=1009294|desc=Promontory fort on Combs Edge, Chapel-en-le-Frith|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nCombs Reservoir is a designated [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] (SSSI). It is particularly important for its 'ephemeral [[bryophyte]]' mosses (such as the rare ''physcomitrium sphaericum'') and [[Marchantiophyta|liverworts]] (''ricca glauca'' and ''fossombronia wondraczekii''). The area is a rich habitat for birdlife including the [[great crested grebe]], [[little ringed plover]], [[snipe]] and [[lapwing]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nCombs Sailing Club has used the reservoir for sailing training and racing since 1950.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.combssailingclub.co.uk/pages/index.php|title=Combs Sailing Club Online|last=|first=|date=|website=www.combssailingclub.co.uk|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n<references group=\"\" responsive=\"1\"></references>\n[[Category:Reservoirs of the Peak District]]\n[[Category:Reservoirs in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Sites of Special Scientific Interest in Derbyshire]]\n[[Category:Peak District]]\n", "name_user": "Douglal", "label": "safe", "comment": "Improved wording", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combs_Reservoir"}
{"title_page": "Basque conflict", "text_new": "{{short description|1959\u20132011 armed and political conflict between Spain and Basque separatists}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox military conflict\n| conflict    = Basque conflict\n| partof      = the [[History of Spain]] and the [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]]\n| image       = Basque conflict.jpg\n| caption     = Clockwise, starting at top left: ETA members at the [[Euzko Gudarostea|2006 Gudari Eguna]] in [[Oiartzun]], [[Gipuzkoa]]; the [[2006 Madrid Barajas International Airport bombing|Madrid Airport bombing]]; a demonstration against ETA in Madrid; pro-ETA graffiti in [[Pasaia]].\n| date        = {{start and end dates|1959|7|31|2011|10|20|df=yes}} ({{Age in months, weeks and days |month1=07|day1=31|year1=1959|month2=10|day2=20|year2=2011}})<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.aljazeera.net/news/europe/2011/10/201110201829708922.html|title=Basque separatists ETA 'end armed struggle'|author=|date=|website=english.aljazeera.net}}</ref>\n| place       = [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]] ([[Spain]], [[France]])\n| result      = Spanish government victory\n*2011: [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]] declares definitive cessation of its armed activity\n*2017: ETA completely disarms\n*2018: ETA completely dissolves\n| status      = \n| combatant1  = '''{{Flagicon image|Flag of Spain (1945\u20131977).svg}} {{flagicon image|Flag of Spain (1977\u20131981).svg}} {{flagicon|Spain|link=no}} [[Spain]]'''\n*[[File:Escudo de la Ertzaintza.svg|18px]] ''[[Ertzaintza]]''\n*{{Nowrap|[[File:Badge of the National Police Corps of Spain.svg|12px]] [[National Police Corps]]}}\n*[[File:Emblem of the Spanish Army.svg|12px]] [[Spanish Army]]\n*[[File:Emblem of the Spanish Civil Guard.svg|12px]] [[Civil Guard (Spain)|Civil Guard]]\n'''{{flagcountry|France}}'''\n*[[File:Grenade bois de cerf.svg|10px]] [[National Gendarmerie]]\n*[[File:Logo-police-nationale-france.svg|20px]] [[National Police (France)|National Police]]\n| combatant2  = '''[[Neo-fascism|Neo-fascist]] paramilitaries:'''\n*[[Batall\u00f3n Vasco Espa\u00f1ol|Spanish Basque Battalion]] {{small|(1975{{en dash}}1981)}}\n*[[GAL (paramilitary group)|Anti-Terrorist Liberation Groups]] {{small|(1983{{en dash}}1987)}}{{efn|The [[GAL (paramilitary group)|Anti-Terrorist Liberation Groups]] (GAL) was supported by some officials of the Spanish government, most notably [[Jos\u00e9 Barrionuevo]].}}\n*[[Triple A (Spain)|Anti-Communist Apostolic Alliance]] {{small|(1976{{en dash}}1983)}}\n*[[Grupos Armados Espa\u00f1oles|Spanish Armed Groups]] {{small|(1979{{en dash}}1980)}}\n*[[Warriors of Christ the King]] {{small|(1968{{en dash}}1980)}}\n*[[Acci\u00f3n Nacional Espa\u00f1ola|Spanish National Action]] {{small|(''unknown'')}}\n*{{Nowrap|[[Antiterrorismo ETA|ETA Anti-Terrorism]] {{small|(1970s)}}}}\n*[[Comandos Antimarxistas|Anti-Marxist Commandos]] {{small|(''unknown'')}}\n| combatant3  = '''[[Basque National Liberation Movement]]:'''\n*{{Nowrap|[[File:Logo of Euskadi Ta Askatasuna.png|18px]] ''[[Euskadi Ta Askatasuna]]''}}\n*[[File:IPARRETARRAK.jpg|18px]] ''[[Iparretarrak]]'' {{small|(1972{{en dash}}2000)}}\n*''[[Iraultza]]'' {{small|(1982{{en dash}}1996)}}\n*[[File:Five Pointed Star Solid.svg|18px]] [[Comandos Aut\u00f3nomos Anticapitalistas|Autonomous Anti-Capitalist Commandos]] {{nowrap|{{small|(late 1970s{{en dash}}1980s)}}}}\n*''[[Irrintzi]]'' {{small|(2005{{en dash}}2009)}}\n*''[[Kale borroka]]''\n*''[[Hordago]]'' {{small|(1980s)}}\n*''[[Euskal Zuzentasuna]]'' {{small|(1977{{en dash}}1979)}}\n| units1      = \n| units2      = \n| units3      = \n| strength1   = \n| strength2   = \n| strength3   = \n| notes       = Total number of casualties is disputed (see [[Basque Conflict#Casualties|Casualties]])\n| casualties1 = 387 Spanish law enforcement agents killed<br />98 off-duty Spanish soldiers killed<br />1 French policeman killed<ref name=varona>{{Cite book|chapter=ETA terrorism victims' experience with restorative encounters in Spain. (Table 16.1 (b) ETA fatalities by status gender and location of victimization)|first= Gema|last=Varona|editor1=Inge Vanfraechem|editor2=Anthony Pemberton|editor3=Felix Mukwiza Ndahinda |page=324|isbn=978-0-415-63433-5|publisher=[[Routledge]]|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yNDpAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA324#v=onepage&q&f=false|location=London and New York|title=Justice for Victims: Perspectives on Rights, Transition and Reconciliation}}</ref><br>343 civilians killed by ETA (including 23 minors)<ref name=varona /><br>2,400 wounded and 1294 permanently incapacitated.<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/>\n| casualties3 = 140 militants killed by law enforcement agencies<br>101 killed in a number of criminal cases involving various parties<br>44 killed due to their own explosives <ref name=\"casualties_total\"/><br/>4,250 wounded<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/><br>~30,000 arrested<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/>\n| casualties2 = Total number of casualties is unknown\n}}\n{{Campaignbox Basque conflict}}\nThe '''Basque conflict''', also known as the '''Spain\u2013ETA conflict''', was an armed and political conflict from 1959 to 2011 between [[Spain]] and the [[Basque National Liberation Movement]], a group of social and political [[Basque nationalism|Basque]] organizations which [[separatism|sought independence]] from Spain and France. The movement was built around the separatist organization [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]],<ref name=\"eu_list\">{{cite web\n| title      = European Union list of terrorist organizations\n| url        = http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/site/en/oj/2006/l_144/l_14420060531en00250029.pdf\n| work       = Official Journal of the European Union\n| year       = 2006\n| accessdate = 1 November 2010\n}}\n</ref><ref name=fto>\n{{cite web\n| title      = Foreign Terrorist Organizations\n| url        = https://www.state.gov/s/ct/rls/other/des/123085.htm\n| work       = Office of the Coordinator for Counterterrorism\n| date       = 15 October 2010\n| accessdate = 1 November 2010\n| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101028113913/http://www.state.gov/s/ct/rls/other/des/123085.htm| archivedate= 28 October 2010 | url-status= dead}}\n</ref> which had launched a campaign of attacks against Spanish administrations since 1959. ETA had been proscribed as a [[List of designated terrorist organizations|terrorist organization]] by the Spanish, British,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/proscribed-terror-groups-or-organisations--2|title=Proscribed terrorist groups or organisations|author=|date=|website=GOV.UK}}</ref> French<ref>{{in lang|fr}} [https://pastel.diplomatie.gouv.fr/editorial/actual/ael2/bulletin.asp?liste=20040601.html#Chapitre14 French list of terrorist organizations, in the annex of Chapter&nbsp;XIV]</ref> and [[U.S. State Department list of Foreign Terrorist Organizations|American]]<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/j/ct/rls/other/des/123085.htm Foreign Terrorist Organizations (FTOs)]. Retrieved on 16 April 2013.</ref> authorities at different moments. The conflict took place mostly on Spanish soil, although to a smaller degree it was also present in France, which was primarily used as a safe haven by ETA members. It was the longest running violent conflict in modern Western Europe.<ref name=\"basque_conflict_gorka\">{{cite web| title      = The Basque Conflict: New ideas and Prospects for Peace| url        = http://www.usip.org/files/resources/sr161.pdf | work       = Gorka Espiau Idoiaga| date       = April 2006| accessdate = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101018174308/http://www.usip.org/files/resources/sr161.pdf| archivedate= 18 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> It has been sometimes referred to as \"Europe's longest war\".<ref name=\"bbcnews_war\">{{cite news| title      = Eyewitness: ETA's shadowy leaders | url        = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/from_our_own_correspondent/545414.stm| work       = news.bbc.co.uk| date       = 2 December 1999| accessdate = 1 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nThe terminology is controversial.<ref name=\"ELM\">{{cite news| title      = El 'Basque conflict', para Wikipedia | url        = http://www.elmundo.es/pais-vasco/2013/12/02/529be31661fd3d6d748b4581.html| |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=2 December 2013 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> \"Basque conflict\" is preferred by [[Basque nationalist]] groups, including those opposed to ETA violence.<ref name=\"NYT1\">{{cite news| title      = More Basque Violence | url        = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/04/opinion/04iht-edwoodworth.html?_r=1&| work       = [[The New York Times]]| date       = 3 August 2009| accessdate = 7 January 2014}}</ref> Others, such as a number of Basque academics and historians commissioned to draft a report on the subject by the Basque government,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/03/11/actualidad/1426103143_149437.html|title=No hubo conflicto vasco, sino totalitarismo de ETA|first=Luis R.|last=Aizpeolea|date=11 March 2015|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT1\"/> reject the term, seeing it as legitimate state agencies fighting a terrorist group which had been responsible for the vast majority of deaths.<ref>{{cite news |last=Ceberia Belaza |first=M\u00f3nica |date=20 October 2011 |title=Las 700 \"consecuencias del conflicto\" |trans-title=The 700 \"consequences of the conflict\" |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2011/10/20/actualidad/1319144401_806536.html |language=Spanish |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Spain |access-date=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"totalitar\">{{cite news |last=Aizpeolea |first=Luis |date=11 March 2015 |title=No hubo conflicto vasco, sino totalitarismo de ETA |trans-title=There wasn't a Basque Conflict, only ETA totalitarianism |url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2015/03/11/actualidad/1426103143_149437.html |language=Spanish |newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]] |location=Spain |access-date=20 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe conflict had both political and military dimensions. Its participants included politicians and political activists on both sides, the [[abertzale left]] (Basque nationalist left) and the Spanish government, and the security forces of Spain and France fighting against ETA and other small organizations, usually involved in the [[kale borroka]] (Basque youth guerrilla violence). Far-right paramilitary groups fighting against ETA were also active in the 1970s and 1980s.\n\nAlthough the debate on [[Basque nationalism|Basque independence]] started in the 19th century, the armed conflict did not start until ETA was created in 1959. Since then, the conflict resulted in the deaths of more than 1,000 people, including police and [[security officer]]s, members of the armed forces, Spanish politicians, journalists and civilians and some ETA members. There also were thousands of people injured, dozens kidnapped and a disputed number going into exile, either to flee from the violence or to avoid capture by Spanish or French police or by [[Europol]]/[[Interpol]].<ref name=\"casualties_total\">{{cite web |title=Datos significativos del conflicto vasco, 1968\u20132003 |url=http://www.euskonews.com/0256zbk/gaia25604_01.html |work=Eusko News |year=2003 |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"exile_elmundo\">{{cite web |title=El Foro de Ermua culpa a Ibarretxe del exilio forzoso de 119.000 vascos |url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2005/02/26/espana/1109457574.html |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=26 February 2005 |accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October 2011, ETA announced a \"definitive cessation of its armed activity\".<ref name=EITB20111020a>{{cite news|title=Armed group ETA announces 'definitive cessation of its armed activity'|url=http://www.eitb.com/en/news/politics/detail/760589/armed-group-eta-announces-definitive-cessation-its-armed-activity/|accessdate=20 October 2011|publisher=EITB.com|date=20 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111022212320/http://www.eitb.com/en/news/politics/detail/760589/armed-group-eta-announces-definitive-cessation-its-armed-activity/|archive-date=22 October 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=BBC20111020>{{cite news |title=Basque group Eta says armed campaign is over|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15393014|accessdate=20 October 2011 |publisher=BBC News |date=20 October 2011}}</ref> Spanish premier [[Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero]] described the move as \"a victory for democracy, law and reason\".<ref name=BBC20111020/>\n\n==Definition of the conflict==\nThe term \"Basque conflict\" is used either to define:\n\n1 the broad political conflict between a part of [[Basque Country (autonomous community)|Basque]] society and the initially Francoist and later Constitutional model of the Spanish [[Autonomous communities of Spain|decentralized state]]\n\n2 exclusively describe the armed confrontation between the separatist group [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]] and the Spanish state\n\n3 a mixture of both perspectives.\n\nFrance was not initially involved in the conflict with ETA nor was it ever targeted by the organization, and the French only slowly began to cooperate with Spanish law enforcement, beginning in 1987, regarding the conflict.{{citation needed|date=March 2017}} Unlike the British participation in [[The Troubles|the conflict in Northern Ireland]], the Spanish armed forces were never deployed or involved in the Basque conflict, although they represented one of ETA's major targets outside the Basque Country.{{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n\nJos\u00e9 Luis de la Granja, Santiago de Pablo and Ludger Mees argue that the term Basque conflict, while technically correct in several languages as equivalent of 'question' or 'problem', should not give the impression of a war between Euskal Herria and the states of Spain and France, preferring the terms ''problema'' or ''cuesti\u00f3n'' (problem or question), that would encompass both the problems in the integration of the Basque territories in the contemporary Spanish state and also the secular problems of cohabitation among the Basques themselves.{{Sfn|Granja Saiz|Pablo|Mees|2011|p=431}}\n\nAccording to Paddy Woodworth in a 2009 article in ''[[The New York Times]]'',\n\n{{blockquote|The core issue is whether there is a \u201cBasque conflict\u201d at all. Spanish public opinion, on both left and right, generally denies that there is, and sees the problem as akin to smashing a criminal mafia. But Basque nationalists, including a big majority who abhor ETA\u2019s methods, believe there is a deep underlying political conflict about Basque self-determination. They want this question to be addressed with the same imagination and courage as the British and Irish governments used in talking to the [[Irish Republican Army|IRA]].\n\nHowever, even raising this issue has become almost taboo among most Spaniards. They regard the Basque country, in the words of one pro-Spanish Basque politician I have interviewed, as \u201cnot just a part of Spain, but the heart of Spain.\u201d<ref name=\"NYT1\"/>}}\n\nAccording to Gaizka Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla, the narrative of the existence of a secular conflict between Basques and Spaniards has been one of the most used tropes by ETA and the abertzale left as pretext for the activity of the former.{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|pp=43-45}} Jos\u00e9 Antonio P\u00e9rez P\u00e9rez points out that the perception of a war between an occupying Spain and a basque people defender of the basque liberties and victim of genocide would have served as justifying framework of the ETA armed activity.{{Sfn|P\u00e9rez P\u00e9rez|2015|pp=94-95}} According to Luis Castells and Fernando Molina the formulation of the existence of two symmetric violences, that would allow for a split of responsibilities between ETA and the states of Spain and France, carrying therefore a dilution of the responsibility of ETA, is a narrative heavily espoused by the Abertzale left, that also would present ETA as an inevitable historic response to the secular conflict.{{Sfn|Castells Arteche|Molina Aparicio|2013|p=225}} According to Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla, in spite of the end of the armed activity, the narrative of the basque conflict, fixed and divulgated by abertzale organic intellectuals such as historians Francisco Letamendia and Jose Mari Lorenzo, publicists such as I\u00f1aki Ega\u00f1a or Eduardo Renobales or journalists such as [[Luis N\u00fa\u00f1ez Astrain]],{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|p=48}} would be still useful as suggestive message in order to delegitimize the current democratic system, mixing victims with victimaries and equating the Basque case to real conflicts such as those of [[South Africa]] and [[Northern Ireland]].{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|p=56}}\n\nThis idea has been rejected, for example, by Jos\u00e9 Maria Ruiz Soroa<ref name=CanonNacionalista>{{cite book|last=Ruiz Soroa|first=Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda|title=El Canon Nacionalista|url=http://paralalibertad.org/wp-content/uploads/Ruiz_Soroa.pdf |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 September 2013}}</ref> and by the main constitutionalist Spanish parties. Some politicians have gone as far as rejecting the existence of even a political conflict and refer only to the action of a terrorist organisation against the rule of law.<ref>{{cite news|last=F\u00e9rnandez D\u00edaz|first=Jorge|title=Fern\u00e1ndez D\u00edaz: 'No ha habido conflicto pol\u00edtico, sino terrorismo'|url=http://www.intereconomia.com/noticias-gaceta/politica/fernandez-diaz-no-habido-conflicto-politico-sino-terrorismo-20120918|accessdate=29 May 2013|newspaper=La Gaceta|date=18 September 2012}}</ref> A group of Basque historians argued that, rather than a Basque Conflict, the situation in the Basque Country was one of \"ETA totalitarianism.\"<ref name=\"totalitar\"/> In 2012, Antonio Basagoiti, the head of the Basque branch of the People's Party admitted the existence of a Basque conflict, but stated that it was a political one between different entities in the Basque country.<ref name=\"conflict_elmundo\">{{cite web |title=Basagoiti admite la existencia de un conflicto que no justifica a ETA |url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2012/01/12/paisvasco/1326364575.html |work=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]] |date=12 January 2012 |accessdate=7 January 2014}}</ref> Joseba Louzao and Fernando Molina argue that the idea of pluralism used by a part of Basque historiography relates more to a particular state of the public sphere ('plurality') rather than to a positive engagement of the several political and social actors ('pluralism');{{sfn|Louzao|Molina|2014|p=320}} according to them, the appeal to pluralism finally led to its conceptual voidment and banalization, allowing for it to be subsumed within the metanarrative of the basque conflict.{{sfn|Louzao|Molina|2014|p=322}}\n\n[[Amaiur]] Senator Urko Aiartza and Dr Julen Zabalo have written that\n\n{{blockquote|There is no unanimous agreement when it comes to determining the reasons for the so-called Basque conflict. According to different sources, it is either a long conflict with historical roots, an instrument of Basque nationalist politics, an attempt to impose a privilege, or evidence of the state's obstinacy. Whichever of these may be the case, an understanding of the historical relations between the Basque provinces and the Spanish and French states is indispensable in order to explain the present conflict.<ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.berghof-conflictresearch.org/documents/publications/transitions_basque.pdf |last=Urko Aiartza and Julen Zabalo|title=The Basque Country: The Long Walk to a Democratic Scenario Berghof Transitions Series No. 7|year=2010|publisher=Berghof Conflict Research|isbn=978-3-941514-01-0 |accessdate=1 September 2013 |page=7}}</ref>}}\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|Basque nationalism}}\n\nThe [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]] ({{lang-eu|Euskal Herria}}) is the name given to the geographical area located on the shores of the [[Bay of Biscay]] and on the two sides of the western [[Pyrenees]] that spans the border between France and Spain. Nowadays, this area roughly belongs to three different political structures: the [[Basque autonomous community]], also known as Euskadi, and [[Navarre]] in Spain, and the three Northern Basque historical provinces ([[Labourd]], [[Lower Navarre]] and [[Soule]]), administratively part of the French department of Pyr\u00e9n\u00e9es-Atlantiques. Approximately 3,000,000 people [[Basque Country (greater region)#Demographics|live in the Basque Country]].\n\n[[Basque people]] have managed to preserve their own identifying characteristics such as their own [[Basque culture|culture]] and [[Basque language|language]] throughout the centuries and today a large part of the population shares a collective consciousness and a [[Basque nationalism|desire to be self-governed]], either with further political autonomy or full independence. For instance, the football club [[Athletic Bilbao]], maintains a [[Athletic Bilbao signing policy|signing policy]] of only recruiting Basque born or raised players. Over the centuries, the Basque Country has maintained various levels of political [[self-governance]] under different Spanish political frameworks. Nowadays, Euskadi enjoys the highest level of self-governance of any nonstate entity within the European Union.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Autonomy games, tensions with the regions ahead of next March's general election in libia\n| url = http://www.economist.com/node/9833306?story_id=9833306| work = economist.com| date = 27 September 2007| accessdate = 1 November 2010}}</ref> However, tensions about the type of relationship the Basque territories should maintain with the Spanish authorities have existed since the origins of the Spanish state and in many cases have fuelled military confrontation, such as the [[Carlist Wars]] and the [[Spanish Civil War]].\n\nFollowing the 1936 coup d'\u00e9tat that overthrew the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish republican government]], a civil war between [[Nationalist Spain|Spanish nationalist]] and republican forces broke out. Nearly all Basque nationalist forces, led by the [[Basque Nationalist Party]] (PNV) sided with the Republic, even though Basque nationalists in \u00c1lava and Navarre fought along Basque Carlists on the side of Spanish nationalists. The war ended with the victory of the nationalist forces, with General [[Francisco Franco]] establishing a dictatorship that lasted for almost four decades. During [[Spanish state|Franco's dictatorship]], Basque language and culture were banned, institutions and political organisations abolished (to a lesser degree in Alava and Navarre), and people killed, tortured and imprisoned for their political beliefs. Although repression in the Basque Country was considerably less violent than in other parts of Spain,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2016/04/12/actualidad/1460482561_623398.html|title=Euskadi evita mirarse en el espejo del pasado|first=Jos\u00e9 Luis|last=Barber\u00eda|date=12 April 2016|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds}}</ref> thousands of Basques were forced to go into exile, usually to Latin America or France.\n\nInfluenced by [[wars of national liberation]] such as the [[Algerian War]] or by conflicts such as the [[Cuban Revolution]], and disappointed with the weak opposition of the PNV against Franco's regime, a young group of students formed ETA in 1959. It first started as an organization demanding the independence of the Basque Country, from a socialist position, and it soon started its [[List of ETA attacks|armed campaign]]. According to Xos\u00e9 Manoel N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas, ETA became a socialist and revolutionary organization using violence after inner struggles related both to the difficulties found in applying a Third World model of national liberation in an already industrialized territory and the division between purely nationalist stances (such as the Branka splinter group) and the revolutionary ones.{{Sfn|N\u00fa\u00f1ez Seixas|2007|p=72}}\n\nETA has instructed their militants to systematically denounce torture by the Spanish Forces.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.publico.es/politica/eta-alecciono-al-comando-t.html |title=ETA aleccion\u00f3 al 'comando' de la T-4 sobre c\u00f3mo denunciar torturas &#124; P\u00fablico |publisher=Publico.es |date=2008-01-14 |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lainformacion.com/disturbios-conflictos-y-guerra/terrorismo/encargado-PNV-denuncia-torturas-etarras_0_935006937.html|title=As\u00ed es c\u00f3mo ETA ped\u00eda a sus militantes que denunciaran... \u00a14.000 torturas!|last=LaInformacion|date=|website=lainformacion.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.larazon.es/historico/txeroki-admite-que-la-denuncia-de-torturas-de-igor-portu-era-falsa-RJLA_RAZON_92761|title=\"Txeroki\" admite que la denuncia de torturas de Igor Portu era falsa|first=La|last=Raz&#243;n|date=17 February 2009|website=larazon.es}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline==\n\n===1959\u20131979===\nETA's first attacks were sometimes approved of by a part of the Spanish and Basque societies, who saw ETA and the fight for independence as a fight against the Franco administration. In 1970, several members of the organization were condemned to death in the ''Proceso de [[Burgos]]'' (Burgos Trial), although international pressure resulted in commutation of the death sentences.<ref>{{cite news | title = Carrero, Franco y ETA| url = http://www.diariovasco.com/prensa/20061226/opinion/carrero-franco_20061226.html| work = diariovasco.com| language = Spanish| date = 26 December 2006| accessdate = 1 November 2010}}</ref> ETA slowly became more active and powerful, and in 1973 the organisation was able to kill the [[Prime Minister of Spain|president of the Government]] and possible successor of Franco, [[Luis Carrero-Blanco, 1st Duke of Carrero-Blanco|Luis Carrero Blanco]]. From that moment on, the regime became tougher in their struggle against ETA: many members died in shootouts with security forces and police carried out big raids, such as the arrest of hundreds of members of ETA in 1975, after the infiltration of [[Mikel Lejarza|a double agent]] inside the organisation.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = Entre la traici\u00f3n y la heroicidad| url = http://www.elpais.com/articulo/cine/traicion/heroicidad/elpepuculcin/20041105elpepicin_4/Tes\n| work = elpais.com| language = Spanish| date = 5 November 2004| accessdate = 1 November 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn mid-1975, a political bloc known as ''Koordinadora Abertzale Sozialista'' (KAS) was created by Basque nationalist organisations. Away from the PNV, the bloc comprised several organisations formed by people contrary to the [[Far-right politics|right-wing]] Franco's regime and most of them had their origins in several factions of ETA, which was part of the bloc as well.<ref>{{cite news\n| title = ETA: la dictadura del terror, KAS| url = http://www.elmundo.es/eta/entorno/kas.html| work = elmundo.es| language = Spanish| year = 2009| accessdate = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101117045837/http://www.elmundo.es/eta/entorno/kas.html| archivedate= 17 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> They also adopted the same ideology as the armed organisation, socialism. The creation of KAS would mean the beginning of the Basque National Liberation Movement.\n\nIn November 1975, Franco died and Spain started [[Spanish transition to democracy|its transition to democracy]]. Many Basque activists and politicians returned from exile, although some Basque organizations were not legalized as had happened with other Spanish organizations.<ref name=\"gara_oct2010\">{{cite news | title = Siempre acosados pero m\u00e1s vivos que nunca| url = http://www.gara.net/paperezkoa/20101030/229233/es/Siempre-acosados-pero-mas-vivos-que-nunca| work = gara.net| language = Spanish| date = 30 October 2010| accessdate = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101101042045/http://www.gara.net/paperezkoa/20101030/229233/es/Siempre-acosados-pero-mas-vivos-que-nunca| archivedate= 1 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> On the other side, the death of Franco elevated [[Juan Carlos I]] to the throne, who chose [[Adolfo Su\u00e1rez]] as [[Prime Minister of Spain]]. Following the approval of the [[Spanish Constitution of 1978|Spanish constitution in 1978]], a [[Statute of Autonomy of the Basque Country|Statute of Autonomy]] was promulgated and approved in referendum. The Basque Country was organized as an [[Autonomous Communities of Spain|Autonomous Community]].\n[[File:Altsasuko Mahaia (1978).jpg|thumb|right|310px|The Alsasua meeting is considered to be the beginning of Herri Batasuna and the Abertzale left]]\nThe new Spanish constitution had overwhelming support around Spain, with 88.5% voting in favour on a turnout of 67.1%. In the three provinces of the Basque Country, these figures were lower, with 70.2% voting in favour on a turnout of 44.7%. This was due to the call to abstention by EAJ-PNV and the creation of a coalition of Abertzale left organisations brought together to advocate for \"no\" in the [[Spanish constitutional referendum, 1978|referendum]], as they felt that the constitution did not meet their demands for independence. The coalition was the beginning of the political party [[Batasuna|Herri Batasuna]], which would become the main political front of the Basque National Liberation Movement. The coalition had its origins in another one made two years before, named ''Mesa de [[Alsasua]]''.<ref name=\"gara_oct2010\"/> ETA also felt that the constitution was unsatisfactory and intensified their armed campaign: 1978 to 1981 were ETA's bloodiest years with more than 230 people killed. Around 1975, the first far right paramilitary organizations (to which former [[Organisation arm\u00e9e secr\u00e8te|OAS]] members joined) that fought against ETA and its supporters had been created, such as the [[Triple A (Spain)|Triple A]] (Alianza Apost\u00f3lica Anticomunista), [[Guerrilleros de Cristo Rey]], [[Batall\u00f3n Vasco Espa\u00f1ol|Batall\u00f3n Vasco-espa\u00f1ol]] (BVE) and Antiterrorismo ETA (ATE);<ref name=elpais>{{cite news|newspaper=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|url=http://elpais.com/diario/1998/08/13/espana/902959204_850215.html|date=1998-08-13|title=La guerra sucia contra ETA germin\u00f3 tras el asesinato de Carrero Blanco|last1=Pa\u00eds|first1=Ediciones El}}</ref>{{Refn|group=n|There was a lapse of 17 months between the end of the attacks by these groups and the start of the activities of the GAL in October 1983 with the [[killing of Lasa and Zabala]], already under the government of Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez.<ref name=elpais />}} 41 deaths and 36 wounded have been reported in attacks blamed on paramilitary far-right organisations in the 1977\u20131982 period.<ref name=elpais />\n\nAlso in the late 1970s, several Basque nationalist organizations, such as [[Iparretarrak]], Hordago or Euskal Zuzentasuna, started to operate in the French Basque Country. An anarchist breakaway of ETA, [[Comandos Aut\u00f3nomos Anticapitalistas]], also started carrying out attacks around the Basque Country. A similar but smaller organization to ETA, [[Terra Lliure]], appeared demanding independence for the [[Pa\u00efsos Catalans|Catalan Countries]]. The Basque conflict had always had an influence on the Catalan society and politics,{{how|date=January 2017}} due to the similarities{{Which|date=January 2017}} between Catalonia and the Basque Country.\n\n===1980\u20131999===\nDuring the process of electing [[Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo, 1st Marquis of la R\u00eda de Ribadeo|Leopoldo Calvo-Sotelo]] as Spain's new president in February 1981, [[Antonio Tejero|Civil Guards]] and [[Spanish Army|army members]] broke into the [[Congress of Deputies (Spain)|Congress of Deputies]] and held all deputies at gunpoint. One of the reasons that led to the [[23-F|coup d'\u00e9tat]] was the increase of ETA's violence. The coup failed after the King called for the military powers to obey the Constitution. Days after the coup, ETA's faction [[ETA political-military|politiko-militarra]] started its disbanding, with most of its members joining [[Euskadiko Ezkerra]], a leftist nationalist party away from the Abertzale left. [[Spanish general election, 1982|General elections]] were held in 1982, and [[Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez]], from the [[Spanish Socialist Workers' Party|Socialist Workers' Party]] became the new president, while Herri Batasuna won two seats. In the Basque Country, [[Carlos Garaikoetxea]] from the PNV became [[lehendakari]] in 1979. During those years, hundreds of members of Herri Batasuna were arrested, especially after some of them sang the [[Eusko Gudariak]] in front of Juan Carlos I.<ref name=\"gara_oct2010\"/>\n\nAfter Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez's victory, the [[Grupos Antiterroristas de Liberaci\u00f3n]] (GAL), death squads established by officials belonging to the Spanish government, were created. Using [[state terrorism]], the GAL carried out dozens of attacks around the Basque Country, killing 27 people. It targeted ETA and Herri Batasuna members, although sometimes civilians were also killed. The GAL were active from 1983 until 1987, a period referred to as the Spanish [[Dirty War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.noticiasdegipuzkoa.com/ediciones/2008/10/18/politica/euskadi/d18eus20.1310616.php |title=Las 27 v\u00edctimas de la verg\u00fcenza: la guerra sucia del GAL se prolong\u00f3 durante cuatro duros a\u00f1os |work=noticiasdegipuzkoa.com |date=18 October 2008 |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081022080546/http://www.noticiasdegipuzkoa.com/ediciones/2008/10/18/politica/euskadi/d18eus20.1310616.php |archivedate=22 October 2008 }}</ref> ETA responded to the dirty war by intensifying its attacks: the organisations started carrying out massive car bomb attacks in [[Madrid]] and [[Barcelona]], such as the [[Hipercor bombing]], which killed 21 civilians. After the attack, most of the Spanish and Basque political parties signed many pacts against ETA, such as the ''Madrid pact'' or the ''Ajuria-Enea pact''. It was during this time that Herri Batasuna got its best results: it was the most voted party in the [[Basque autonomous community]] for the [[European Parliament election, 1987 (Spain)|European Parliament elections]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elecciones.mir.es/MIR/jsp/resultados/comunes/detalleResultado.jsp?tipoAmbito=1&tipoEleccion=6&cdEleccion=7&anio=1987&mes=6&numVuelta=1&nombreEleccion=Parlamento+Europeo&horaCierre=20:00&horaAvance1=14:00&horaAvance2=18:00&cdCCAA=99&cdProvincia=0&descripcion=total |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110525163456/http://www.elecciones.mir.es/MIR/jsp/resultados/comunes/detalleResultado.jsp?tipoAmbito=1&tipoEleccion=6&cdEleccion=7&anio=1987&mes=6&numVuelta=1&nombreEleccion=Parlamento+Europeo&horaCierre=20%3A00&horaAvance1=14%3A00&horaAvance2=18%3A00&cdCCAA=99&cdProvincia=0&descripcion=total |url-status=dead |archive-date=25 May 2011 |title=Elecciones Parlamento Europeo Junio 1987 |work=elecciones.mir.es |year=1987 |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 November 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Muralbelfast2.jpg|thumb|300px|A republican mural in Belfast showing solidarity with the [[Basque nationalism]].]]\n\nWhile talks between the Spanish government and ETA had already taken place in the late 1970s and early 1980s, which had led to the dissolution of ETA (pm),{{clarify|date=October 2017}} it was not until 1989 that both sides held formal peace talks. In January, ETA announced a 60-day ceasefire, while negotiations between ETA and the government were taking place in [[Algiers]]. No successful conclusion was reached, and ETA resumed violence.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.elmundo.es/eta/negociaciones/gonzalez.html |title=Felipe Gonz\u00e1lez y las conversaciones de Argel |work=elmundo.es |year=2009 |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 November 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030114221/http://www.elmundo.es/eta/negociaciones/gonzalez.html |archivedate=30 October 2010 |url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nAfter the end of the dirty war period, France agreed to cooperate with the Spanish authorities in the arrest and [[extradition]] of ETA members. These would often travel to and from between the two countries using France as a base for attacks and training. This cooperation reached its peak in 1992, with the arrest of all ETA leaders in the town of [[Bidart]]. The raid came months before the [[1992 Summer Olympics|1992 Olympic Games]] in Barcelona, with which ETA tried to gather worldwide attention with massive attacks around Catalonia.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.expansion.com/especiales/20aniversario/20diasespana/eta.html| title= Bidart: la ca\u00edda de la c\u00fapula de ETA| work= expansion.com| language    = Spanish| accessdate=1 November 2010}}</ref> After that, ETA announced a two-months ceasefire, while they restructured the whole organisation and created the [[kale borroka]] groups.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.elmundo.es/cronica/2001/310/1001319590.html| title= \"Txelis\", el padre de la kale borroka |work= elmundo.es/cronica|date=23 September 2001|language= Spanish| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101105145824/http://www.elmundo.es/cronica/2001/310/1001319590.html| archivedate= 5 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1995, ETA tried to kill [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Aznar]], who would become prime minister of Spain one year later, and Juan Carlos I. That same year, the organisation launched a peace proposal, which was refused by the government. On the following year, ETA announced a one-week ceasefire and tried to engage peace talks with the government, a proposal that was once again rejected by [[People's Party (Spain)#Aznar years (1989-2004)|the new conservative government]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.elmundo.es/eta/negociaciones/treguas_eta.html| title       = La dictadura del terror: Las treguas de ETA| work        = elmundo.es/| language    = Spanish| year        = 2009| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101106062045/http://www.elmundo.es/eta/negociaciones/treguas_eta.html| archivedate= 6 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 1997, young councillor [[Miguel \u00c1ngel Blanco]] was kidnapped and killed by the organisation. The killing produced a widespread rejection by Spanish and Basque societies, massive demonstrations and a loss of sympathisers, with even some ETA prisoners and members of Herri Batasuna condemning the killing.<ref>{{cite news\n| url         = http://www.elpais.com/articulo/espana/dia/todos/fuimos/Miguel/Angel/Blanco/elpepunac/20070708elpepinac_3/Tes| title       = El d\u00eda en que todos fuimos Miguel \u00c1ngel Blanco| work        = elpais.com| language    = Spanish| date        = 8 July 2007| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| last1 = Pa\u00eds| first1 = Ediciones El}}</ref> That same year, the Spanish government arrested 23 leaders of Herri Batasuna for allegedly collaborating with ETA. After the arrest, the government started to investigate Herri Batasuna's ties with ETA, and the coalition changed its name to Euskal Herritarrok, with [[Arnaldo Otegi]] as their leader.<ref name=\"rtve_politica\">{{cite web| url         = http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20090123/las-siglas-politicas-eta/730.shtml| title       = Las siglas pol\u00edticas de ETA| work        = rtve.es\n| date        = 23 January 2009| language    = Spanish| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101203015459/http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20090123/las-siglas-politicas-eta/730.shtml| archivedate= 3 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nIn the [[Basque parliamentary election, 1998|1998 Basque elections]], the Abertzale left got its best results since the 1980s, and Euskal Herritarrok became the third main force in the Basque Country. This increase of support was due to the declaration of a ceasefire by ETA one month before the elections.<ref name=\"rtve_politica\"/> The ceasefire came after Herri Batasuna and several Basque organisations, such as the PNV, which at that time was part of the PP's government, reached a pact, named ''[[Lizarra]] pact'', aimed at putting pressure on the Spanish government to make further concessions towards the independence. The Basque nationalist forces agreed in defining the Basque conflict as of political nature and in presenting ETA and the Spanish State as the two conflicting parties.{{Sfn|Mata|2005|p=89}} Influenced by the [[Northern Ireland peace process]], ETA and the Spanish government engaged in peace talks, which ended in late 1999, after ETA announced the end of the ceasefire.<ref>{{cite news |last=Gooch |first=Adela |date=29 November 1999 |title=Basque separatists end 14-month truce |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/1999/nov/29/2 | work=[[The Guardian]] |location=[[United Kingdom]] |access-date=12 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n===2000\u20132009===\nIn 2000, ETA resumed violence and intensified its attacks, especially against senior politicians, such as [[Ernest Lluch]]. At the same time, dozens of ETA members were arrested and the Abertzale left lost some of the support it had obtained in the 1998 elections. The breaking of the truce provoked Herri Batasuna's dissolution and its reformation into a new party called Batasuna. Following disagreements over the internal organization of the Batasuna, a group of people broke away to form a separate political party, [[Aralar Party|Aralar]], present mainly in Navarre.<ref>{{cite web| url         = http://www.aralar.net/aralar-partido/historia| title         = Historia de Aralar| work         = aralar.net| language         = Spanish| accessdate         = 1 November 2010| archive-url         = https://web.archive.org/web/20110112042404/http://www.aralar.net/aralar-partido/historia| archive-date         = 12 January 2011| url-status         = dead}}</ref> In 2002, the Spanish government passed a law, named ''Ley de Partidos'' (Law of Parties), which allows the banning of any party that directly or indirectly condones terrorism or sympathises with a terrorist organisation. As ETA was considered a terrorist organisation and Batasuna did not condemn its actions, the government banned Batasuna in 2003. It was the first time since Franco's dictatorship that a political party had been banned in Spain.<ref>{{cite news| url         = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/2857437.stm| title       = Batasuna banned permanently| work        = news.bbc.co.uk| date        = 17 March 2003\n| accessdate  = 1 November 2010}}</ref> That same year, Spanish authorities closed the only newspaper written fully in Basque, ''[[Egunkaria]]'', and journalist were arrested, due to allegations of links with ETA which were dismissed by Spanish justice seven years later.<ref>[http://egunkaria.info/international/wp-content/uploads/2010/04/veredicto.pdf The whole sentence of Audiencia Nacional in the ''Egunkaria'' case], passed on 12 April 2010.</ref> In 1998, another newspaper, ''[[Egin (newspaper)|Egin]]'', had already been closed on similar grounds that were also dismissed by Spanish justice eleven years later.<ref>{{cite web| url         = http://www.euskalherria.info/?q=es/node/1052| title       = The Basque newspaper Egunkaria closed down by the Spanish government| work        = euskalherria.info| date        = 21 February 2003\n| accessdate  = 1 November 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.gara.net/paperezkoa/20090527/139211/es/El-Supremo-rebaja-condenas-18-98-desmonta-ahora-tesis-usada-para-cerrar-Egin \"El Supremo rebaja las condenas del 18/98 y desmonta ahora la tesis usada para cerrar \u00abEgin\u00bb\"], ''Gara'', 27 May 2009.</ref><ref>[http://www.gara.net/agiriak/20090526_fallo_TS_1898.doc The whole sentence of Tribunal Supremo in the ''Egin'' case], 22 May 2009.</ref>\n\n[[File:Repulsa atentado lazkao 2009.jpg|thumb|Demonstrations after every ETA attack were common around Spain]]\n\nAfter the government falsely accused ETA of carrying out the [[2004 Madrid train bombings]], the conservative government lost the elections in favour of the Socialist Workers' Party, and [[Jos\u00e9 Luis Rodr\u00edguez Zapatero]] became the new president of Spain.<ref>{{cite news| url         = https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSL16484708| title       = Analysis \u2013 Spain's PM down but not out after ETA bomb| work        = reuters.com| date        = 16 January 2007| accessdate  = 1 November 2010\n| first=Jason| last=Webb}}</ref> One of Zapatero's first actions was to engage in new peace talks with ETA. In mid-2006, the organisation [[ETA's 2006 ceasefire declaration|declared a ceasefire]], and conversations between Batasuna, ETA and the Basque and Spanish governments started. Despite the claims of peace talks ending in December, when ETA broke the truce with a [[2006 Madrid Barajas International Airport bombing|massive car bomb]] at the [[Madrid-Barajas Airport]], a new round of conversations took place on May 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u00a1Habr\u00e1 guerra para 40 a\u00f1os o m\u00e1s!|url=http://politica.elpais.com/especiales/2011/conversaciones-secretas-eta/|accessdate=2 January 2014|newspaper=El Pa\u00eds|date=5 December 2011}}</ref> ETA officially ended the ceasefire in 2007, and resumed its attacks around Spain.<ref>{{cite news| url         = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11183574| title       = Who are ETA?| work        = bbc.co.uk/news| date        = 5 September 2010| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101103214820/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-11183574| archivedate= 3 November 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> From that moment on, the Spanish government and police intensified their struggle both against ETA and the Abertzale left. Hundreds of members of the armed organisation were arrested since the end of the truce, with four of its leaders being arrested in less than one year. Meanwhile, the Spanish authorities banned more political parties such as [[Eusko Abertzale Ekintza|Basque Nationalist Action]],<ref>{{cite news| url         = http://edition.cnn.com/2008/WORLD/europe/09/16/spain.basque/index.html| title       = Spain bans political party for ETA links| work        = edition.cnn.com| date        = 16 September 2009| accessdate  = 1 November 2010}}</ref> [[Communist Party of the Basque Homelands]] or [[D3M|Demokrazia Hiru Milioi]]. Youth organisations such as [[Segi (organization)|Segi]] were banned, while members of trade unions, such as [[Langile Abertzaleen Batzordeak]] were arrested.<ref>{{cite web| url         = http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20091013/detienen-a-otegi-a-otros-nueve-dirigentes-otro-golpe-a-batasuna-sede-del-sindicato-lab/296175.shtml\n| title       = Detienen a Otegi y a otros nueve dirigentes en otro golpe a Batasuna en la sede del sindicato LAB| work        = rtve.es| language    = Spanish| date        = 13 October 2009| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101025053853/http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20091013/detienen-a-otegi-a-otros-nueve-dirigentes-otro-golpe-a-batasuna-sede-del-sindicato-lab/296175.shtml| archivedate= 25 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> In 2008, Falange y Tradici\u00f3n, a new Spanish far-right nationalist group appeared, carrying out dozens of attacks in the Basque Country. The organisation was dismantled in 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url        = http://www.noticiasdenavarra.com/2010/03/09/politica/navarra/falange-y-tradicion-queria-captar-adeptos-y-comprar-armas-para-proseguir-sus-ataques| title        = Falange y Tradici\u00f3n quer\u00eda captar adeptos y comprar armas para proseguir sus ataques| work        = noticiasdenavarra.com| language        = Spanish| date        = 9 March 2010| accessdate        = 27 December 2010| archive-url        = https://archive.today/20120629042550/http://www.noticiasdenavarra.com/2010/03/09/politica/navarra/falange-y-tradicion-queria-captar-adeptos-y-comprar-armas-para-proseguir-sus-ataques| archive-date        = 29 June 2012| url-status        = dead| df        = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2010===\nIn 2009 and 2010, ETA suffered even more blows to its organization and capacity, with more than 50 members arrested in the first half of 2010.<ref>{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20100821/cronologia-detenciones-presuntos-miembros-eta-2010/318594.shtml| title       = Cronolog\u00eda de las detenciones de presuntos miembros de ETA en el 2010| work        = rtve.es| language    = Spanish| date        = 21 August 2010| accessdate  = 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101027000713/http://www.rtve.es/noticias/20100821/cronologia-detenciones-presuntos-miembros-eta-2010/318594.shtml| archivedate= 27 October 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref> At the same time, the banned Abertzale left started to develop documents and meetings, where they committed to a \"democratic process\" that \"must be developed in a complete absence of violence\". Due to these demands, ETA announced in September that they were [[ETA (separatist group)|stopping their armed actions]].<ref>{{cite web| url        = http://www.ezkerabertzalea.info/irakurri.php?id=5032| title        = The Abertzale Left about ETA's announce to cease armed activities| work        = ezkerabertzalea.info| date        = 13 September 2010| accessdate        = 1 November 2010| archiveurl        = https://web.archive.org/web/20101124130650/http://ezkerabertzalea.info/irakurri.php?id=5032| archivedate        = 24 November 2010| url-status        = dead| df        = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===2011===\n\n[[File:Konferentzia.ogv|thumb|400px|The final declaration of the [[Donostia-San Sebasti\u00e1n International Peace Conference]], read by [[Bertie Ahern]], with Basque language subtitles.]]\n\nOn 17 October, an [[Donostia-San Sebasti\u00e1n International Peace Conference|international peace conference]] was held in Donostia-San Sebasti\u00e1n, aimed at promoting a resolution to the Basque conflict. It was organized by the Basque citizens' group [[Lokarri]], and included leaders of Basque parties,<ref name=nyt20111018>{{cite news|last=Minder|first=Raphael|title=Peace Talks Pressure Basque Separatists to Disarm|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/10/18/world/europe/peace-talks-pressure-basque-separatists-to-disarm.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=The New York Times|date=18 October 2011}}</ref> as well as six international personalities known for their work in the field of politics and pacification: [[Kofi Annan]] (former UN Secretary-General), [[Bertie Ahern]] (former Prime Minister of Ireland), [[Gro Harlem Brundtland]] (international leader in sustainable development and public health, former Prime Minister of Norway), [[Pierre Joxe]] (former Interior Minister of France), [[Gerry Adams]] (president of Sinn F\u00e9inn, member of the Irish Parliament) and [[Jonathan Powell (aide)|Jonathan Powell]] (British diplomat who served as the first Downing Street Chief of Staff). [[Tony Blair]] \u2013 former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom \u2013 could not be present due to commitments in the Middle East,<ref name=EITB20111017>{{cite news|title=Annan and Adams top list of experts at Donostia Peace Conference|url=http://www.eitb.com/en/news/politics/detail/757117/annan-adams-top-list-experts-donostia-peace-conference/|accessdate=18 October 2011|publisher=EITB.com|date=17 October 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111021003611/http://www.eitb.com/en/news/politics/detail/757117/annan-adams-top-list-experts-donostia-peace-conference/|archive-date=21 October 2011|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> but he supported the final declaration. The former US President [[Jimmy Carter]] (2002 Nobel Peace Prize) and the former US senator [[George J. Mitchell]] (former United States Special Envoy for Middle East Peace) also backed this declaration.<ref>{{cite news|author=Europa Press|title=Tony Blair y Jimmy Carter suman sus apoyos a la declaraci\u00f3n de la Conferencia|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2011/10/19/espana/1319043378.html|accessdate=19 October 2011|newspaper=El Mundo|date=19 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe conference resulted in a five-point statement that included a plea for [[ETA (separatist group)|ETA]] to renounce any armed activities and to demand instead negotiations with the Spanish and French authorities to end the conflict.<ref name=nyt20111018/> It was seen as a possible prelude to the end of ETA's violent campaign for an independent Basque homeland.<ref>{{cite news|title=International negotiators urge Eta to lay down weapons|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-15330766|accessdate=19 October 2011|publisher=BBC News|date=17 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nThree days later \u2013 on 20 October \u2013 ETA announced \"definitive cessation of its armed activity\".<ref name=EITB20111020a/><ref name=BBC20111020/> They said they were ending their 43-year armed campaign for independence and called on Spain and France to open talks.<ref name=EITB20111020a/> Spanish premier [[Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero]] described the move as \"a victory for democracy, law and reason\".<ref name=BBC20111020/>\n\n==Aftermath==\n\n===2012===\nOn 28 May 2012, ETA members Oroitz Gurruchaga and Xabier Aramburu were arrested in southern France.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://politica.elpais.com/politica/2012/05/27/actualidad/1338133362_978546.html|title=Detenido el jefe del aparato militar de ETA, seg\u00fan Interior|language=Spanish}}</ref>\n\n===2016===\nThough the group declared a permanent ceasefire, the French police made a declaration warning that ETA had made no steps towards dissolution.<ref>{{cite web|author=/ 23 Septiembre, 2016 - 00:00 |url=http://gaceta.es/noticias/policia-francesa-alerta-eta-avanza-disolucion-23092016-1652 |title=La Polic\u00eda francesa alerta de que ETA no avanza hacia la disoluci\u00f3n &#124; La Gaceta |publisher=Gaceta.es |date= June 2017|accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref> It is also known that ETA was still hoarding weaponry and explosives, several members guarding explosives have been detained since their permanent ceasefire declaration.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ashifa Kassam in Madrid |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/sep/22/senior-members-of-basque-separatist-group-eta-arrested-in-france |title=Senior members of Basque separatist group Eta arrested in France &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref>\n\n===2017===\nIn March 2017 ETA declared that it would disarm completely by 8 April.<ref>https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/03/17/basque-separatist-group-eta-launch-disarmament-initiative/ Retrieved 17 April 2017.</ref>  On that date, civilian 'go-betweens' ([[Artisans of Peace (Basque conflict)|Artisans of Peace]]) handed a list of 8 coordinates to the authorities which showed the locations of weapons caches in southwestern France used by the group.<ref name=\"reuters.com\">https://www.reuters.com/article/us-spain-eta-idUSKBN1790YK Retrieved 17 April 2017.</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Agence France-Presse |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2017/apr/08/it-has-been-done-eta-hands-over-weapons-in-france |title='It has been done': Eta hands over weapons in France &#124; World news |publisher=The Guardian |date= |accessdate=2018-04-22}}</ref> The caches were reported to have contained 120 firearms, about 3 tonnes of explosives and several thousand rounds of ammunition,<ref name=\"reuters.com\"/> which were seized by the Spanish and French authorities. The Spanish government stated that ETA will gain no impunity for their disarmament, and urged the group to dissolve formally.\n\n===2018===\nOn May 3, 2018, during a ceremony held at the Centre for Humanitarian Dialogue's (HD) in Geneva, Switzerland, it was confirmed by the center's Director that the ETA (Euskadi ta Askatasuna) had disbanded forever was [https://www.hdcentre.org/updates/hd-announces-etas-official-final-declaration-that-it-has-disbanded-forever/ officially sent and verified]. Following this [https://www.hdcentre.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/ETA-declaration-English.pdf announcement], a ceremony was organized in Northern Basque Country, in Kanbo (Cambo-les-Bains) where the \"declaration of Arnaga\" was pronounced.\n\n==Casualties==\nEstimates of the total number of conflict-related deaths vary and are highly disputed. The number of deaths caused by ETA is consistent among different sources, such as the Spanish Interior Ministry, the Basque government, and most major news agencies. According to these sources, the number of deaths caused by ETA are 829. This list does not include [[Bego\u00f1a Urroz]], killed in 1960 when she was 22 months old. Although this killing was attributed by [[Ernest Lluch]] to ETA in 2000, as revealed in El Pa\u00eds,<ref name=\"first_victim\">{{cite web| title      = La primera v\u00edctima de ETA| work       = [[El Pa\u00eds]]| url        = http://www.elpais.com/articulo/reportajes/primera/victima/ETA/elpepusocdmg/20100131elpdmgrep_1/Tes\n| language   = Spanish| accessdate = 1 November 2010}}</ref> the attack was committed by the DRIL (''Directorio Revolucionario Ib\u00e9rico de Liberaci\u00f3n'').<ref>{{cite news\n| last1         = Ser\u00f3n\n| first1        = Lu\u00eds\n| last2         = San Jos\u00e9\n| first2        = Tais\n| date         = 2013-05-05\n| title        = Bego\u00f1a Urroz sigue siendo una v\u00edctima del terrorismo, pero no de ETA\n| url          = http://www.eitb.eus/es/noticias/politica/detalle/1332012/begona-urroz-eta-dril-entrevista-euskadi-irratia-xabier-montanya/\n| newspaper    = EITB\n| location     =\n| access-date  = 2016-09-28\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n| last1         = Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla\n| first1        = Gaizka\n| date         = 2014-06-28\n| title        = La primera v\u00edctima mortal de ETA no fue Bego\u00f1a Urroz\n| url          = http://latribunadelpaisvasco.com/not/1480/la-primera-victima-mortal-de-eta-no-fue-begona-urroz/\n| newspaper    = La Tribuna del Pa\u00eds Vasco\n| location     =\n| access-date  = 2016-09-28\n}}</ref>\n\nSome organizations such as the ''Colectivo de V\u00edctimas del Terrorismo en el Pa\u00eds Vasco'' raise the death toll of ETA's victims to 952. This is due to the inclusion to the list of several unresolved attacks such as the [[Hotel Corona de Arag\u00f3n fire]].<ref name=\"casualties_eta_952\">{{cite web|title=Balance de dolor |work=Colectivo de V\u00edctimas del Terrorismo en el Pa\u00eds Vasco |url=http://www.covite.org/covite_balancedolor.php |language=Spanish |accessdate=1 November 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100704211219/http://www.covite.org/covite_balancedolor.php |archivedate=4 July 2010 }}</ref> The [[Asociaci\u00f3n de V\u00edctimas del Terrorismo]] also includes the victims of the Corona de Arag\u00f3n fire on its list of ETA's deaths.<ref name=\"casualties_avt\">{{cite web| title= V\u00edctimas del Terrorismo| work= [[Asociaci\u00f3n de V\u00edctimas del Terrorismo]]| url= http://www.avt.org/victimasdelterrorismo.php| language= Spanish| accessdate= 1 November 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101016084037/http://www.avt.org/victimasdelterrorismo.php| archivedate= 16 October 2010| url-status= dead| df= dmy-all}}</ref> Sources have suggested ETA responsibility in the crash of [[Iberia Airlines Flight 610]] at Monte Oiz (Bilbao) on 19 February 1985 with 148 killed <ref name=\"Monte_Oiz\">{{cite web | title=La enigm\u00e1tica tragedia del monte Oiz: \u00bffue o no un atentado de ETA |url=http://www.periodistadigital.com/politica/sucesos/2012/02/20/tragedia-monte-oiz-eta-terrorismo-alhambra-granada-euskadi-lopez-bravo-padilla-patino-eta-lemoniz.shtml | date=20 February 2012 | accessdate= 24 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the Basque National Liberation Movement side the Euskal Memoria foundation, linked to the abertzale left,{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|pp=52-53}}<ref name=abc>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.es/20111207/espana/abcp-elabora-censo-victimas-propias-20111207.html|work=[[ABC (Spain)|ABC]]|title=ETA elabora un censo de \"v\u00edctimas\" propias e incluye a muertos por infarto o accidente|date=2011-12-07}}</ref> and born in 2009 with the proclaimed purpose of having a database in order to \"counter the lies from the State\",{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|pp=52-53}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.euskalmemoria.eus/es/Publicaciones/Revistas/Revista_Euskal_Memoria_n%C2%BA_1|title=Euskal Memoria Fundazioa (2010), 1}}</ref> list the number of deaths on their side as 474 in the period between 1960 and 2010. [[News agency]] Eusko News states that at least 368 people died on the Basque nationalist side. Most of the lists also include an undefined number of suicides caused by the conflict, coming from former ETA members, tortured people or policemen. Additional death causes in the Euskal Memoria list such as deaths to natural illnesses, a death of an ETA member due to a stroke suffered while having sexual relations, deaths due to the accidental activation of ETA bombs by ETA members, deaths in car and plane accidents, the death of common criminals, the death of a football fan killed by rivals, and deaths abroad such as a death in a mine in Nicaragua, a missionary killed by guerrilla in Colombia, two Uruguayans in Uruguay, two guerrilla collaborators in El Salvador and a protester in Rome have been claimed.{{Sfn|Fern\u00e1ndez Soldevilla|2016|pp=52-53}}<ref name=abc />\n\n===Responsibility===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:400px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:left;\"|Responsibility for killing\n|-\n\n!  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:left;\"|Responsible party\n\n!  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:right;\"|No.\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| Euskadi Ta Askatasuna || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 829<ref name=\"casualties_eta_829\">{{cite web\n |title        = \u00daltimas v\u00edctimas mortales de ETA: Cuadros estad\u00edsticos\n |work         = Ministerio del Interior\n |url          = http://www.interior.gob.es/prentsa-3/balantzeak-21/ultimas-victimas-mortales-de-eta-cuadros-estadisticos-630\n |language     = Spanish\n |accessdate   = 5 December 2013\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131226085229/http://www.interior.gob.es/prentsa-3/balantzeak-21/ultimas-victimas-mortales-de-eta-cuadros-estadisticos-630\n |archive-date = 26 December 2013\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| Paramilitary and far-right groups || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 72<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/>\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"|  Spanish security forces  || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 169<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/>\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| Other cases || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 127<ref name=\"casualties_total\"/>\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| '''Total''' || style=\"text-align:right;\"| '''1197'''\n|}\n\n===Status===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:400px;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:center;\"|ETA deaths by status of victim<ref name=\"casualties_eta_829\"/>\n|-\n\n!  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:left;\"|Status\n\n!  style=\"background:#ffdead; text-align:right;\"|No.\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| Civilian || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 343\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| Members of security forces || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 486\n|-\n\n! colspan=\"2\"  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:center;\"|of whom:\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Guardia Civil]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 203\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Cuerpo Nacional de Polic\u00eda]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 146\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Spanish Army]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 98\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Municipal police (Spain)|Policia Municipal]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 24\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Ertzaintza]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 13\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Mossos d'Esquadra]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1\n|-\n|  style=\"background:#efefef; text-align:left;\"| [[Police Nationale|French National Police]] || style=\"text-align:right;\"| 1\n|}\n\n==Prisoners==\n{{Main|Basque National Liberation Movement Prisoners}}\n\nThe Spanish and French law enforcement agencies have convicted a number of people for terrorist activities (primarily murder or attempted murder), or for belonging to ETA or organizations subservient to this organization. A small minority have been imprisoned for \"enaltecimiento del terrorismo\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Detenida Jone Amezaga para su ingreso en prisi\u00f3n.|url=http://ccaa.elpais.com/ccaa/2014/12/15/paisvasco/1418643705_952662.html|accessdate=5 May 2015|issue=El Pais, 15 December 2014}}</ref> which literally translates as \"glorification of terrorism\".  The number of people incarcerated reached a peak of 762 in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|title=ETA pulveriza su r\u00e9cord hist\u00f3rico de pistoleros presos: 762|url=http://www.abc.es/20091202/nacional-terrorismo/pulveriza-record-historico-pistoleros-20091202.html|publisher=ABC|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> These prisoners are jailed in prisons all over France and Spain \"to make it difficult for ETA to communicate with them,\" according to non-revealed sources.<ref>{{cite web|title=Large separatist protest calls on Spain to repatriate Basque prisoners to jails close to home|url=http://www.foxnews.com/world/2013/01/12/large-separatist-protest-calls-on-spain-to-repatriate-basque-prisoners-to-jails/|publisher=Fox News, 12 January 2013|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Rajoy no revisar\u00e1 la dispersi\u00f3n de presos si ETA no se disuelve.|url=http://www.larazon.es/9231-rajoy-no-revisara-la-dispersion-de-presos-si-eta-no-se-disuelve-QLLA_RAZON_423100#.Ttt1NI9LqRYRYWM|publisher=La Razon, 31 December 2011|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref> There have been 5,500 claims or complaints of torture or mistreating in police custody.<ref>[[Manuela Carmena|Carmena, Manuela]]; Landa, Jon Mirena; M\u00fagica, Ram\u00f3n; Uriarte, Juan M\u00ba (2013),  [http://www.lehendakaritza.ejgv.euskadi.eus/contenidos/informacion/documentos_paz_convivencia/eu_def/adjuntos/giza_eskubideen_urraketak.pdf Euskal kasuan gertaturiko giza eskubideen urraketei buruzko oinarrizko txostena (1960-2013)], Eusko Jaurlaritza.</ref>\n\nFor the [[Abertzale left]] this is one of the most emotive issues relating to Basque Nationalism. Demonstrations calling for their return to the Basque region often involve thousands of people.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thousands protest over Basque prisoners|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/223763.stm|publisher=BBC, 28 November 1998|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Thousands of Basque protesters march for ETA prisoners in defiance of Madrid|url=http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2014/01/12/world/thousands-of-basque-protesters-march-for-eta-prisoners-in-defiance-of-madrid/#.VMkTNyhBA-Z|publisher=Japan times, 12 January 2014|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Huge march in Spain after ban on Eta prisoner rally|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-25700221|publisher=BBC, 11 January 2014|accessdate=28 January 2015}}</ref> Currently there is a highly publicised campaign calling for the return of these dispersed prisoners to the Basque Country. Its slogan is \"Euskal presoak- Euskal Herrira\" (\"Basque prisoners- to the Basque Country\").<ref>{{cite web|title=Thousands protest in Bilbao over conditions for ETA prisoners|url=http://www.expatica.com/es/news/country-news/Thousands-protest-in-Bilbao-over-conditions-for-ETA-prisoners_366762.html|publisher=Expatica, 12 January 2013|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nSome groups such as [[Etxerat]] have been calling for a general [[amnesty]], similar to that which took place in [[Northern Ireland]] in 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paramilitary prisoners are freed|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/854970.stm|publisher=BBC, 28 July 2000|accessdate=29 January 2015}}</ref> The [[Government of Spain|Spanish government]] has so far rejected moves to treat all prisoners in the same way.  Instead they opened the 'Via Nanclares' in 2009 which is a way for individual prisoners to get better conditions, and eventually gain limited release.  It involves the individual asking for forgiveness, distancing themselves from ETA and paying compensation.<ref>{{cite web|title=La 'V\u00eda Nanclares' explicada en diez preguntas|url=http://www.eldiario.es/zonacritica/Via-Nanclares-explicada-preguntas_6_4959511.html|publisher=eldiario, 15 May 2012|accessdate=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Basque Country (greater region)#Politics|Politics in the Basque Country]]\n*[[List of conflicts in Europe]]\n*[[International Contact Group (Basque politics)]]\n*[[History of the Basque people#Present|History of the Basque people]]\n*[[The Troubles]] \u2013 Conflict in Northern Ireland\n*[[War In Donbass]] \u2013 Donetsk and Lugansk People's Republics, Ukraine\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* {{Cite journal|title=Bajo la sombra de Vichy: el relato del pasado reciente en la Euskadi actual|first=Luis|last=Castells Arteche|first2=Fernando|last2=Molina Aparicio|journal=Ayer|