,946|| [[Avianca Costa Rica]], [[Avianca Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|38|| {{flagicon|Spain}} [[Barcelona-El Prat Airport|Barcelona, Spain]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{increase}} 80,730|| [[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|39|| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Foz do Igua\u00e7u International Airport|Foz do Igua\u00e7u, Brazil]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{increase}} 79,989||[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|40|| {{flagicon|UK}} [[Gatwick Airport|London-Gatwick, United Kingdom]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 50,701||[[British Airways]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|41|| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Teniente General Benjam\u00edn Matienzo International Airport|Tucum\u00e1n, Argentina]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 49,367||[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|42|| {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Montr\u00e9al\u2013Pierre Elliott Trudeau International Airport|Montr\u00e9al-Trudeau, Canada]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 44,412||[[Air Canada Rouge]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|43|| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Mart\u00edn Miguel de G\u00fcemes International Airport|Salta, Argentina]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 40,552||[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|44|| {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Andr\u00e9s Sabella G\u00e1lvez International Airport|Antofagasta, Chile]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 36,872||[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|45|| {{flagicon|Colombia}} [[Alfonso Bonilla Arag\u00f3n International Airport|Cali, Colombia]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 35,927||[[Avianca Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|47|| {{flagicon|Venezuela}} [[Sim\u00f3n Bol\u00edvar International Airport (Venezuela)|Caracas, Venezuela]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 30,997||[[Avior Airlines]], [[Estelar Latinoamerica]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|46|| {{flagicon|Venezuela}} [[General Jos\u00e9 Antonio Anzo\u00e1tegui International Airport|Barcelona, Venezuela]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 29,453||[[Avior Airlines]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|48|| {{flagicon|USA}} [[Washington-Dulles International Airport|Washington-Dulles, United States]]|| style=\"text-align:center;\"|{{decrease}} 26,675||[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n|-\n|}\n</center>\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n* November 27, 1962: [[Varig Flight 810]], a [[Boeing 707|Boeing 707-441]] registration PP-VJB flying from [[Rio de Janeiro-Gale\u00e3o International Airport|Rio de Janeiro-Gale\u00e3o]] to Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport, after initiating an overshoot procedure at the suggestion of the [[control tower]] because it was too high, proceeded to start another approach when it crashed into La Cruz peak, 8 miles from the airport. Possibly there was a misinterpretation of navigation instruments. All 97 passengers and crew aboard died.<ref name=PP-VJB_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19621127-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 707-441 PP-VJB Lima-Callao International Airport (LIM)|author=Harro Ranter|date=27 November 1962|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first=Carlos Ari C\u00e9sar | last=Germano da Silva | title=O rastro da bruxa: hist\u00f3ria da avia\u00e7\u00e3o comercial brasileira no s\u00e9culo XX atrav\u00e9s dos seus acidentes 1928-1996 | chapter=Back course | publisher=EDIPUCRS | edition=2 | place=Porto Alegre | year=2008 | pages=217\u2013222 | isbn=978-85-7430-760-2 | language=Portuguese}}</ref>\n* May 8, 1964: an [[Argentine Air Force]] [[Douglas C-54]] registration T-47 flying from [[Buenos Aires]] to Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport crashed into a sand dune during approach in poor visibility conditions, killing 46 of 49 people on board.<ref name=T-47_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19640508-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Douglas C-54A-DO (DC-4) T-47 Lima International Airport (LIM)|author=Harro Ranter|date=8 May 1964|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* December 1985: a bomb planted by the Maoist [[Shining Path]] terrorist movement, exploded in the parking lot and killed five people, including a child.<ref>{{cite book |last1=America |title=Terrorist Group Profiles |date=1989 |publisher=DIANE Publishing |isbn=9781568068640 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=55BZmIJ9xd8C&pg=PA108&lpg=PA108&dq=lima+airport+bomb#v=onepage&q=lima%20airport%20bomb&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n* August 6, 1986: an explosion of unknown origin occurred at a restroom in the domestic terminal.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Thomas |first1=Andrew R. |title=Aviation Security Management [3 volumes] |date=2008 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9780313346538 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=Xq9zCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA217&lpg=PA217&dq=lima+airport+bomb#v=onepage&q&f=false |language=en}}</ref>\n* December 8, 1987: a [[Peruvian Navy]] [[Fokker 27|Fokker 27-400M]] registration AE-560 flying from [[Pucallpa]] to Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport chartered by the [[1987 Alianza Lima air disaster|Alianza Lima]] [[Association football|football team]] crashed into the [[Pacific Ocean]] shortly before landing. A malfunctioning cockpit indicator made the crew believe that the [[landing gear]] was not properly deployed and locked, so they requested the [[control tower]] allow the plane to make a low pass for a visual check by ground personnel. After receiving the confirmation that the [[landing gear]] was down, the aircraft circled the airport for another attempt to land, but plunged into the ocean instead, killing all on board except the pilot.<ref name=AE-560_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |title=ASN Aircraft accident Fokker F-27 Friendship 400M AE-560 Lima-Jorge Chavez International Airport (LIM) |author=Harro Ranter |date=8 December 1987 |accessdate=4 June 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100527050835/http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19871208-1 |archivedate= 27 May 2010 }}</ref>\n* March 10, 1989: an [[Aero Condor]] [[Britten-Norman Islander|Britten-Norman BN-2A Islander]] registration OB-1271 flying from [[Nazca]] to Jorge Chavez International Airport crashed into a building during approach killing all on board, apparently due to fuel exhaustion.<ref name=OB-1271_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19890310-2|title=ASN Aircraft accident IRMA/Britten-Norman BN-2A Islander OB-T-1271 Lima|author=Harro Ranter|date=10 March 1989|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* January 25, 1991: a car bomb placed by the [[Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement]] (MRTA), killed two Peruvians and wounded several others. The attack occurred in a context of condemnation, by left-wing armed groups and political movements, of [[Operation Desert Storm]]; minutes after the attack, the US Embassy in Lima was attacked with an [[Rocket propelled grenade|RPG]] and [[small arms]] fire by the MRTA.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Organization/20308.pdf |title=Documents |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/20308.pdf |website=www.state.gov}}</ref>\n* July 24, 1992: five American Airlines employees, charged with cleaning and baggage loading duties, were wounded by a bomb. This happened during the weekend in which Shining Path enforced a 48-hour nationwide \"armed strike\" that aimed at paralyzing, among other services, public transportation.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Mickolus |first1=Edward F. |last2=Simmons |first2=Susan L. |title=Terrorism, 1992-1995: A Chronology of Events and a Selectively Annotated Bibliography |date=1997 |publisher=ABC-CLIO |isbn=9780313304682 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=UIBzCC0c2McC&pg=PA190&lpg=PA190&dq=american+airlines+lima+1992#v=onepage&q=american%20airlines%20lima%201992&f=false |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Shining Path Rebels Flaunt |title=Their Power With Strike In Peru |url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/1992-07-26/news/9202210624_1_bus-drivers-car-bombs-guerrillas |website=tribunedigital-sunsentinel |language=en}}</ref> \n*January 22, 1993: three bullets hit the right side of the fuselage of American Airlines Flight 917 (inbound from Miami) while either landing  or taxiing on the runway after landing. There were no casualties and damage to the plane was minimal. Despite Shining Path (SP) claiming responsibility for the attack, a subsequent investigation failed to identify the actual assailants. Airport authorities reportedly stated that the source of the shots was accidental, originating in a security guard working in the perimeter.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Peruvian rebels bomb Coca-Cola plant |title=Kill mayoral candidates; shots fired at American Airlines jet) |url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1993/01/22/Peruvian-rebels-bomb-Coca-Cola-plant-kill-mayoral-candidates-shots-fired-at-American-Airlines-jet/7707727678800/ |website=UPI |language=en}}</ref>  The incident, occurring in the context of a [[Internal conflict in Peru|decade-long leftist insurgency against the Peruvian state]], happened in the midst of a surge of terrorist attacks and assassinations during that month which also targeted US interests and businesses.<ref name=\"state.gov\">{{cite web |last1=Organization/19813.pdf |title=Documents |url=https://2009-2017.state.gov/documents/organization/19813.pdf |website=www.state.gov}}</ref>\n*October 25, 1993: Months after the shooting of Flight 917, the cargo office of American Airlines suffered moderate property damage after the explosion of a bomb, placed under a minibus parked near the departure terminal. Shining Path involvement was suspected.<ref name=\"state.gov\"/>\n* April 15, 1995: an Imperial Air [[Tupolev 134|Tupolev Tu-134A-3]] registration OB-1553 flying from [[Cusco]] to Jorge Chavez International Airport suffered a tire failure after departure. The crew decided to continue the flight to Lima, but the left main [[landing gear]] did not extend during landing. There were no fatalities, but the aircraft was damaged beyond repair.<ref name=OB-1553_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19950415-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Tupolev 134A-3 OB-1553 Lima-J Chavez International Airport (LIM)|author=Harro Ranter|date=15 April 1995|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n* October 2, 1996: [[AeroPeru Flight 603|Flight 603]], an [[AeroPeru|AeroPer\u00fa]] [[Boeing 757|Boeing 757-23A]] registration N52AW flying the [[Miami]]-[[Lima]]-[[Santiago, Chile]] route crashed into the [[Pacific Ocean]] some minutes after its takeoff from Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport, killing all on board. The accident investigation found that masking tape was accidentally left over the [[Pitot-static system|static ports]] during maintenance, rendering the [[airspeed indicator]], [[altimeter]] and [[Variometer|vertical speed indicator]] unreliable.<ref name=N52AW_ASN>{{cite web|url=http://aviation-safety.net/database/record.php?id=19961002-0|title=ASN Aircraft accident Boeing 757-23A N52AW Lima, Peru|author=Harro Ranter|date=2 October 1996|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n*On October 11, 2013 an [[Airbus A320]] (registration N492TA) from Taca Airlines, made an emergency landing at 8:20 am Local Time. The pilot declared an emergency due to smoke in the cockpit. The aircraft was en route from Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport to [[El Salvador International Airport]], [[San Salvador]], [[El Salvador]]. There were 31 passengers plus crew on board. The aircraft landed safely.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inac.gob.ni/2013/10/reporte-aeronautico-0613/|title=INAC|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Fraport|Fraport AG]]\n* [[Aeropuertos del Per\u00fa]]\n* [[CORPAC]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.lima-airport.com/}}\n\n{{Portalbar|Peru|Aviation}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jorge Chavez International Airport}}\n[[Category:Airports in Peru]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Callao Region]]\n[[Category:Transport in Lima]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Lima airport|The airport in Lima, Ohio|Lima Allen County Airport}}\n{{Infobox airport\n| name         = Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport\n| nativename   = {{lang|es|Aeropuerto Internacional Jorge Ch\u00e1vez}}\n| image        = Airp0rt lima peru.jpg\n| image-width  = 250\n| IATA         = LIM\n| ICAO         = SPJC\n| type         = Public international\n| owner        =\n| operator     = [[Lima Airport Partners]]\n| city-served  = [[Lima, Peru|Lima]], [[Peru]]\n| location     = [[Callao]], [[Peru]]\n| hub          =\n<div>\n*[[Avianca Peru]]\n*[[LATAM Per\u00fa]]\n*[[Sky Airline]]\n*[[Star Per\u00fa]]\n*[[Viva Air Per\u00fa]]\n</div>\n| elevation-f  = 113\n| elevation-m  = 34\n| coordinates  = {{coord|12|01|19|S|077|06|52|W|region:PE|display=inline,title}}\n| website      = {{URL|https://www.lima-airport.com/}}\n| pushpin_map            = Peru Lima\n| pushpin_mapsize        =\n| pushpin_map_alt        =\n| pushpin_map_caption    = Location of airport in Lima\n| pushpin_relief         =\n| pushpin_image          =\n| pushpin_label          = LIM\n| pushpin_label_position =\n| pushpin_mark           =\n| pushpin_marksize       =\n| metric-elev  = yes\n| metric-rwy   = yes\n| r1-number    = 15/33\n| r1-length-f  = 11,506\n| r1-length-m  = 3,507\n| r1-surface   = [[Asphalt]]\n| stat-year    = 2018\n| stat1-header = Passengers\n| stat1-data   = 23,723,193\n| stat2-header = Freight ([[tonne]]s)\n| stat2-data   = 370,450,587\n| stat3-header = Aircraft movements\n| stat3-data   = 178,578\n| footnotes    = Source: corpac s.a. statistics<ref>{{cite web |last1=Statistics |title=CORPAC S.A. |url=http://www.corpac.gob.pe/Main.asp?T=5274 |website=www.corpac.gob.pe}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:LIM - check in area.jpg|thumb|Check-in area at Jorge Chavez International Airport (Lima, PE)]]\n'''Jorge Ch\u00e1vez International Airport''' {{Airport codes|LIM|SPJC{{nobold|, formerly}} SPIM}}, ('''Aeropuerto Internacional Jorge Ch\u00e1vez'''), is [[Peru]]'s main international and domestic [[airport]]. It is located in [[Callao]], 11&nbsp;kilometers (7&nbsp;mi) from [[Historic Centre of Lima|Lima]], the nation's capital city and 17&nbsp;km (11&nbsp;mi) from [[Miraflores District, Lima|Miraflores]]. During 2017, the airport served 22,025,704 passengers. Historically, the airport was the hub for [[Faucett Per\u00fa|Compa\u00f1\u00eda de Aviaci\u00f3n Faucett]] and [[Aeroperu|Aeroper\u00fa]]. Now it serves as a [[airline hub|hub]] for many aviation companies. The airport was named after Peruvian aviator [[Jorge Ch\u00e1vez]] (1887 - 1910).\n\n==History==\n[[Image:Douglas C-54G OB-R-894 SATCO Lima 20.04.72 edited-3.jpg|thumb|200px|Lima Airport in 1972 with a SATCO [[Douglas DC-4]] operating an internal flight|left]]\n\nLima's first airport was the [[Limatambo International Airport|Limatambo Airport]] in San Isidro. It ceased operations in 1960 due to a lack of space and capacity, and was replaced by the Lima-Callao International Airport. In June 1965, the Lima-Callao airport was renamed the \"Aeropuerto Internacional Jorge Ch\u00e1vez\" after the famous Peruvian aviator, Jorge Ch\u00e1vez Dartnell. In December 1965, the terminal building was officially opened.\n\nWhen it was in operation, [[Compa\u00f1\u00eda de Aviaci\u00f3n Faucett]] had its corporate headquarters on the airport grounds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=PDFarchive |title=Flightglobal/view/1995/1995 |url=https://www.flightglobal.com/pdfarchive/view/1995/1995%20-%200749.html |website=www.flightglobal.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, in order to improve and expand its infrastructure, the government of Peru placed the airport under the management of [[Lima Airport Partners]] (LAP). LAP is now composed of [[Fraport]] and two other minor partners. The air traffic control is managed by the Peruvian Corporation of Airports and Commercial Aviation ([[CORPAC]]). The Peruvian government engaged Jaime Malag\u00f3n, Jerome Jakubik, Paul Slocomb, and [[V\u00edctor M. Marroqu\u00edn]] of Baker and McKenzie international law firm, to oversee the changes.\n\n==Expansion==\n[[File:LIM terminal.jpg|thumb|right|Main terminal]]\nIn February 2005, the first phase of a new renovation and expansion project was completed. This included the Peru Plaza Shopping Center and a new [[concourse]]. In June 2007, a four-star hotel, [[Ramada]] Costa del Sol, opened at the airport.\n\nIn January 2009, the second phase of the terminal expansion was commenced. The terminal has 28 gates, 19 with [[jet bridge|boarding bridges]]. In August 2009, the LAP announced that in 2010, the airport would have a new [[Instrument Landing System]] (ILS CAT III) to help with fog landings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.livinginperu.com/news-9808-advice-peru-lima-airport-to-reach-category-iii-in-2010-with-fog-assist-landing|title=Peru this Week|accessdate=4 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090918124057/http://www.livinginperu.com/news-9808-advice-peru-lima-airport-to-reach-category-iii-in-2010-with-fog-assist-landing|archivedate=18 September 2009}}</ref> 'Arquitectonica\", a Miami-based architectural office and Lima Airport Partners planned a second terminal and expansion of the main terminal.\n\nOn October 24, 2018, the Peruvian state delivered all the land for the expansion and modernization of the Jorge Chavez airport to the airport operator \"Lima Airport Partners\".\nThe estimated investment of 1,200 million USD includes the construction of a new runway, a control tower and a passenger terminal in addition to the existing one.\nOn the other hand, the state will build a new bridge and highway on the current Santa Rosa avenue that will connect directly with the \"costa verde\" highway. \nWorks will be completed in 4 years, by the beginning of the year 2023, and will allow the transist of 40 million passengers per year by 2030.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://tnews.com.pe/vizcarra-hace-entrega-de-terrenos-en-jorge-chavez-y-asegura-anunciadas-inversiones/ |title = VIZCARRA HACE ENTREGA DE TERRENOS EN JORGE CHAVEZ y ASEGURA ANUNCIADAS INVERSIONES &#124; T News}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://rpp.pe/economia/economia/aeropuerto-jorge-chavez-cuando-podras-disfrutar-de-la-ampliacion-del-aeropuerto-jorge-chavez-noticia-1158957 | title=Aeropuerto Jorge Ch\u00e1vez &#124; \u00bfCu\u00e1ndo podr\u00e1s disfrutar de la ampliaci\u00f3n del Aeropuerto Jorge Ch\u00e1vez?}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://gestion.pe/economia/ampliacion-jorge-chavez-permitira-transito-40-millones-pasajeros-2030-nndc-248041 |title = Ampliaci\u00f3n del Jorge Ch\u00e1vez permitir\u00e1 tr\u00e1nsito de 40 millones de pasajeros en 2030|date = 2018-10-24}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nFrom 2010 to 2012, the LAP received the annual Best Airport in South America 2010 award from [[Skytrax]].<ref>[http://www.worldairportawards.com/Awards_2010/bestairport_samerica.htm Lima Airport: Best Airport in South America 2010] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101222151541/http://worldairportawards.com/Awards_2010/bestairport_samerica.htm |date=2010-12-22 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/659143/noticia-jorge-chavez-aeropuerto-lider-sudamerica-2010-segunthe-wall-street-journal|title=Jorge Ch\u00e1vez es el Aeropuerto L\u00edder en Sudam\u00e9rica 2010, seg\u00fan \"The Wall Street Journal\"|author=El Comercio|date=4 June 2015|work=EL COMERCIO|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.airlinequality.com/|title=Airline Rating and Reviews \u2013 Airport Rating and Reviews \u2013 Seat Reviews|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.worldairportawards.com/Awards_2012/bestairport_samerica.htm World Travel Awards 2012] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120422175244/http://worldairportawards.com/Awards_2012/bestairport_samerica.htm |date=2012-04-22 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://peru.com/2012/04/20/actualidad/economia-y-finanzas/aeropuerto-jorge-chavez-fue-elegido-mejor-sudamerica-cuarta-vez-noticia-59807|title=Aeropuerto Jorge Ch\u00e1vez fue elegido el mejor de Sudam\u00e9rica por cuarta vez|work=Per\u00fa.com|accessdate=4 June 2015|date=2012-04-20}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2010, the Sumaq VIP lounge at the airport received its second annual [[Priority Pass]] \"Lounge of the Year 2010\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prioritypass.com/|title=Airport Lounge Access Worldwide \u2013 Priority Pass|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vipclub.com.pe/ingles/la_empresa.htm|title=VIP Club|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prioritypass.com/Press/Priority-Pass-Lounge-of-the-Year-2010.cfm|title=Priority Pass Lounge of the Year 2010 \u2013 Recent News of Interest \u2013 Priority Pass|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/lima/446067/noticia-sala-vip-aeropuerto-jorge-chavez-fue-elegida-mejor-mundo-viajeros|title=La sala vip del aeropuerto Jorge Ch\u00e1vez fue elegida la mejor del mundo por viajeros|author=El Comercio|date=4 June 2015|work=EL COMERCIO|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://elcomercio.pe/economia/462985/noticia-conozca-sala-vip-aeropuerto-jorge-chavez-mejor-mundo|title=Conozca la sala vip del aeropuerto Jorge Ch\u00e1vez, la mejor del mundo|author=El Comercio|date=4 June 2015|work=EL COMERCIO|accessdate=4 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n{{update|section|date=March 2020}}\nTransportation between the airport and the city is provided by taxis, tour buses and vans. [[Airport Express Lima]] is the official bus of Jorge Ch\u00e1vez Airport and operates between the airport and Miraflores. Line 2 and Line 4 of the [[Lima Metro]] are currently under construction, with an airport rail station terminal expected to be open by 2019.\n\n==Facilities==\nThe airport hosts the [[Wyndham Worldwide|Wyndham]] Costa del Sol hotel which is located adjacent to the control tower and the arrivals exit. The hotel is built with noise canceling panels. The Peru Plaza Shopping Center is located near the passenger terminal in the Grand Concourse area. The food court is located near the entrance of the passenger terminal on the second floor and is always open. There is an ice cream vendor selling some special Peruvian flavours such as [[Chirimoya]] and [[Lucuma]].\n\nThe airport has various premium lounges in the departures terminal, such as VIP Peru. For passengers in First class, there is an exclusive salon near the gates, the VIP Club.\n\nOn 12 May 2009, the airport opened Lima Cargo City, a hub for cargo airlines.\n\n==Airlines and destinations==\n===Passenger===\n{{Airport destination list\n<!-- -->\n|[[Aerol\u00edneas Argentinas]] | [[Ministro Pistarini International Airport|Buenos Aires\u2013Ezeiza]] \n<!-- -->\n|[[Aerom\u00e9xico]] | [[Mexico City International Airport|Mexico City]] (resumes May 1, 2020)<ref name=COVIDAMX>{{cite web|url=https://www.aeromexico.com/en-us/actions-covid19|title=Safety Precautions: COVID-19|website=Aerom\u00e9xico|date=April 2020|accessdate=April 7, 2020}}</ref>\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Canada Rouge]] | [[Toronto Pearson International Airport|Toronto\u2013Pearson]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air Europa]] | [[Madrid-Barajas Airport|Madrid]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[Air France]] | [[Charles de Gaulle Airport|Paris\u2013Charles de Gaulle]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[American Airlines]] | [[Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport|Dallas/Fort Worth]], [[Miami International Airport|Miami]]\n<!-- -->\n|[[ATSA Airlines|ATSA]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Atsa Airlines |title=Descubriendo juntos el Per\u00fa |url=https://www.atsaairlines.com/ |website=www.atsaairlines.com |language=en}}</ref> | [[Tnte. Gral. Gerardo P\u00e9rez Pinedo Airport|Atalaya]], [[Chachapoyas Airport|Chachapoyas]], [[Alf\u00e9rez FAP David Figueroa Fernandini Airport|Hu\u00e1nuco]], [[Tingo Maria Airport